Apply the root test.  We compute

\[
L \;=\;\lim_{k\to\infty}\bigl|a_k\bigr|^{1/k}
   \;=\;\lim_{k\to\infty}\Bigl(\frac{k^e}{e^k}\Bigr)^{1/k}
   \;=\;\lim_{k\to\infty}\frac{k^{e/k}}{e}
   \;=\;\frac{1}{e}\,<\,1.
\]

Indeed \(k^{e/k}=e^{(e/k)\ln k}\to e^0=1\).  Since \(L<1\), the series \(\sum_{k=1}^\infty k^e/e^k\) converges (in fact absolutely).

We first rewrite  
\[
a_k \;=\;\frac{2\cdot4\cdot6\cdots(2k)}{(2k)!}
=\frac{\bigl(2^k\,k!\bigr)}{(2k)!}
\,.  
\]  
Now apply the Ratio Test.  Compute

\[
\frac{a_{k+1}}{a_k}
=\frac{2^{\,k+1}(k+1)!/(2(k+1))!}
      {2^k\,k!/(2k)!}
=\;2\,(k+1)\;\frac{(2k)!}{(2k+2)!}
=\frac{2(k+1)}{(2k+2)(2k+1)}
=\frac1{2k+1}\,.
\]

As \(k\to\infty\), \(\frac{a_{k+1}}{a_k}\to0<1\).  Hence by the Ratio Test the series  
\[
\sum_{k=1}^\infty a_k
\]
converges.
